{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_babelfish_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280656896/1921022301/0458.xml":{"full_text":"THE EVENING STAR\nWfcfa Snfay Mowriac Edition.\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\nWEDNESDAY. .February 23, 1921\nTHEODOBE W. NOTES Editoi\nThe Erenlnf Star Newspaper Companj\nlehw Office. llth St. and Penniylranta Are\nNew Tork Office: Tribune Building.\nChicago OCr: First National Bank BntMlne\nuropcan Office: 8 Begent St.. London, England\n1W Erenin* Star, with the Sunday tnornlni\nkdillsij. |s denreeed by carriers within the eit]\nat CO cent* per month: daliy only. 45 cents pe\nMath; Snnday only. 30 cents per month. Or\n4m may be sent by mail, or telephone Mail\nSOB Collection is made by carriers at tbi\nend of each month.\nBate by Mall?Payable in Advance.\nMaryland and Virginia.\n?J o..?j ?q in- 1 mn 7 Of\n?iJu ouiiuajr .x Ji., Daily\nonly 1 yr.. W OO; 1 mo., R0<\nSunday only 1 yr.. $2.40; 1 mo., 20c\nAll Other States.\nDaily and Sunday. 1 yr., |10.00: 1 mo., *R<\nDaily only 1 yr., $7.00; 1 mo.. 6?c\nSunday only lyr.. 3.00: 1 mo.. 25c\nMr. Harding and Congresi.\nThese subjects have been promi\nnent in the discussions at Marion and\nat St. Augustine: The tariff, taxation\nthe merchant marine, the Army, the\nNavy and the best means for promot\nlng world peace.\nOn these subjects Mr. Harding hat\nhad the opinions of men in and oul\nof Congress who are familiar with\nthem. They have called on him by\nInvitation, and with the knowledge\nthat they were expected to lay their\nbest information before him. Pre\nBumably, they have done so.\nOn these subjects President Hard\nlng will at one time or another, and\nsoon, communicate with Congress.\nThat body will be expecting to hear\nfrom him, and, there is reason to believe,\nwill be much influenced by his\nrecommendations.\nIf we can handle these subjects?\nparticularly the first three named?in\na way to satisfy the country and\nfully restore confidence, we may promise\nourselves a return of prosperity\nand a general stabilization of our national\naffairs. A new tariff will put\n\"pep\" into production, a readjustment\nof taxes will remove some complaints\nnow justly made, while a merchant\nmarine operated in the interests of\nAmerican trade will materially advance\nour foreign trade policy.\nMr. Harding then will take hold\nwell prepared for the most important\nwork pressing for attention. If he\ncores at the special session he will\nbe likely to score at the regular session;\nand two scores should go a long\ng way toward the election of another\nI^Mpublican Congress and his re-elecHon\nin 1924.\nThe Cabinet.\nIf the list stands as announced. Mr.\nHarding's official advisers should render\nhim excellent service in the conduct\nof the government's affairs. They\nare hi the prime of life. They are well\ndistributed geographically. They have\nbad marked success in the matter of\ntheir personal affairs. With but two\nexceptions?Mr. Mellon and Mr. Davis\n?they have had experience in politics,\nand are well known to the country.\nTwo of them?Mr. Weeks and Mr.\n/Penby?have served in Congress, and\none?Mr. Fall?is serving there now.\nOne?Mr. Hoover?is known the wide\nWorld over.\nThe appointment of Mr. Denby?\nwell justified on practical gTounds?1\nwill make a popular appeal on sentimental\ngrounds. A man of education\nand high position, twice in a war\nemergency he offered himself and was\naccepted as a private. He was a\ngunner's mate in the Spanish-American\nwar, and a drill sergeant for marines\nin the world war. He received\npromotion in the latter capacity.' Now\nbe goes to the head of the Navy Department.\nHas there ever been a\nmore striking illustration of the fact\nthat the republic is opportunity?\nMr. Harding himself is in the prime\nof life. So we shall have at this important\ntime in our national life a\nstrong chief assisted by strong lieutenants\nshaping the course and responsible\nfor the national welfare. The\ncountry expects success, and should\ndo all in its power to assist in such\nan achievement.\nJudge Landis doubtless regards\nRepresentative Welty as one of those\npeople who consider It their mission\nIn life to make trouble for the umpires.\nThe Berlin idea of Indemnity is\nrlns^lv rplafp^ to that\n?V U(C UCUIUI\nwho decides to let the other people\nworry.\nMuch of the advice President-elect\nHarding received evidently has not\ncaused him to waver in the least.\nSimple Traffic Boles Needed.\nA revision of the city's traffic regulations\nstarted about four months ago\nIs now about complete. The draft of\nthe revised rules has been submitted\nto the Commissioners after an intensive\nstudy by various officials, and\nIt is expected that after the final\nscrutiny they will be adopted and\npublished. They cannot be put into\neffect for thirty days after adoption,\nand thus it will be perhaps the 1st of\nApril before these new rules are enforced.\nWhen the time comes to print these\nrules for official distribution and the\nInstruction of motorists they should\nbe put in the most compact, condensed\nform possible, so that the essential\nprinciples of street use are vividly\nand definitely presented. Much of the\ntraffic trouble of today arises from the\nfact that many street users are really\nnot informed as to the requirements\nand restrictions, particularly in minor\nmatters of street crossing and parkIn*.\nThe essentials of the traffic rules\ncould be printed in a four-page folder.\nHeretofore, however, the rule book\nhas been a pamphlet of such size thai\nprobably not one in twenty has ever\nread it through and understood it.\nIn this matter of traffic regulation\nthe essential point is to get everybody\nIn rhythm. That is to say, to get\neverybody working together on the\nflame basis. Most accidents in the\n\"gtnsta result from' misunderstanding.\nis, of course, much selfishness,\nmanifested by speeding and corner\nI .cutting and Indifference to the ordl'\nM i\nnary rules of safety. But the aver'\nage motor owner will be careful of\nhis car and will do his best to protect\nit from injury. Even an insured car\nis out of commission after a collision,\nand the owner has no use of it until\nr the insurance company may pay the\nrepairs bill,\nr The Commissioners can do, perhaps,\ntheir most effective work for street\nsafety in their final revision of the\nnew rules by aiming at condensation\nand simplification. It has often been\nJ said that there is too much law for\nthe public good. This is perhaps esJ\npecially true in the matter of traffic\nregulation.\n\nMount Vernon.\nA descendant of one of George\nWashington's brothers, in a public\naddress at Nazareth, Pa., the other\nevening recited certain facts regarding\nthe family estate which suggested\nthe possibility that the burial ground at\nMount Vernon might be closed to the\npublic, inasmuch as it was specifically\nexempted from transfer. He now corl\nrects the false impression created by\nhis statement to say that this possi.\nbility was only theoretical, and that\nhe merely intended to note the fact\nthat the tomb of George Washington\nstands upon ground that cannot be\nalienated from the family heritage.\nI Tt? 1 x -s\nhub nu luea mac cne greac American\npatriotic shrine will ever be closed\nto public access.\nThis serves to bring anew to atten.\ntion the question of the proper administration\nof the Mount Vernon es.\ntate. A patriotic organization of\nwomen has saved this place from de,\ncay and from commercial exploitation.\nIt is distressing to think of the\npossibilities of Mount Vernon in strict,\nly private hands as a \"show place\" in\nthe ordinary sense. The Mount Ver.\nnon Association has. by turning back\nall of the fees collected for admission\nI into the maintenance of the estate,\nkept it with notable fidelity to the\nhistorical type and standard. It has\npreserved the atmosphere remarkably. 1\nIt has acquired by purchase numerous\narticles of furnishing that effec\ntively replaced the originals and has\ntraced out and regained many pieces\nthat were part of the equipment in\nWashington's day.\nThe only possible change from the 1\npresent condition would be for the\ngovernment to acquire Mount Vernon\nand to maintain it as a national\nreservation, with suitable guardianship.\nThe sole advantage of such a\ntransfer would be to place the cost\nof maintenance upon the federal taxes\ninstead of upon the admission fees of\nthose who visit it. As the matter now\nstands the public is taxed for the upkeep\nof Mount Vernon by direct contribution.\nUnder national control the\ncost would be distributed among all\nthe people. At the same time it is\nfelt by many that Mount Vernon\nshould be open, free, provided, of\nonnroo V?ot I* ?a\nWm.wv *o vcu ifuxn injury 1\nin consequence of the probably larger\nattendance.\nHowever this may be, it is inter-\neating to know that in theory at least\none part of the estate is inviolate from 1\neither public or alien private owner- t\nship. Inasmuch as that part is the\npoint of chief patriotic interest, it may\nbe suggested with propriety that this\nquestion of the real owner of the grave\nof George Washington should he set-\ntied definitely.\nt\nMr. Boiling's Exoneration.\nIn formally announcing its exonera-\ntion of R. W. Boiling of a charge of\nI improper conduct in connection with\na Ship Board transaction, the House\nspecial committee has closed an inci-\ndent that has given pain to many\nWashlngtonians. Mr. Boiling, a resident\nof the capital for years, in high\nstanding, was accused of dealings that,\nif verified, would have subjected him\nto the severest censure if not to prosecution.\nThe committee, after an ex- 1\nhaustive inquiry, finds no basis for the 1\ncharge. Bevond\n_ ??...vbo aoovcia*\ntion that, Mr. Boiling himself has\nacknowledged publicly, was unfor-\ntunate and injudicious, there was noth-\ning whatever in the matter to warrant\nthe least question as to his in- 1\ntegrity of purpose or action. This\noutcome of the case is gratifying to 1\nMr. Boiling's friends, .who have never\ncredited the accuaatlon~and have hoped\nfor a full, formal exoneration such as\nthat which the committee has now\nrecorded.\nI\nLaw and politics are closely related\nin this country, and leading republicans\ncredit Mr. Harry Daugherty\nwith a legal discernment no less accurate\nthan his political discernment.\nAn Attorney General, after all, is ex-\npected to grasp large ideas and broad\nprinciples. There is always a library\nand a corps of assistants available to\nsupply technical details.\nCommercial travelers contemplate\norganizing a strike to prevent unrea-\nsonably high hotel charges. This Is 1\nstill another idea for bringing down\nthe high cost of living.\n1\nA blizzard offers at least one prob- 1\nlem in railway transportation which 1\ncannot be turned over to the Inter-\nstate Commerce Commission.\nSanta Claus Anally had his vindication,\nalthough (the usefulness of j\nskates and sled9 was a long time in\nmaterializing.\nAir Kail Risks.\nWhile there is every wish to expedite\nthe transport of the mail, it\nmay be doubted if reason exists for\nthe continued use of the airplane for\ni this purpose, in the present state of\naviation art. Fatal accidents are so\nfrequent in this service that a doubt\nhas arisen in the public mind as to\nthe wisdom of seeking to put the air\nmail system on a basis of regularity.\nIt is still virtually an experiment.\nAviation dangers are still great. Yesterday\nthe second fatal accident of\nthe current year appeared at Elko,\nNev., when a plane in a flight that i\nwas intended to establish a San Frans\nclsco-New York speed record fell and I\ni the pilot was killed. Previously since\nthe 1st of January three were killed\nat La Crosse, Wis., while four fatal\naccidents occurred in the air mail i\nI service in 1920, with five deaths, mak-\ning nine deaths in this service in less\nthan fourteen months.\nWhen the airplane mail service was\nestablished it was recognized as an j\nexperiment. But it has been regularized\nand scheduled flights are conducted.\nThe air mail pilots take off 1\non their routes without reference to\nweather, and several of the fatal ac-1'\ncidents have been result of unfavor- j'\nable atmospheric conditions.\nIn addition to the nine men whose I\nlives have been sacrificed in these ac-\ncidents much mail has been destroyed i\nby fire, constituting an irretrievable j1\nloss. The risk attending an air mail!\nletter is much greater than that in-i J\nni/lnnf U II 1 i _\nt- iuriu iv in*; irguiai man sei viue. a\nfeeling prevails that it would, per-j\nhaps, be better to devote the money\nexpended in this expensive experiment\nto the improvement of collection\nand delivery methods in the\nlarger cities, where the mail service\nis yet far from perfect. It is of slight\nadvantage to the user of the mails\nto have his letter transported between\ncities in half the usual time only to\nhave it reach destination little or no\nsooner owing to the congestion in the\nhouse-to-house distribution.\nCriticisms and Cabinets.\nIf \\Ir 1Iarr)in? ull rlistt nrhorl\nby the criticism leveled at the Daugherty\nappointment he can find comfort\nin Mr. Cleveland's experience in the\ncase of the Olney appointment.\nGloomy predictions are not always\nfulfilled.\nRichard Olney was a lawyer of high\nstanding at home, but unknown to\nthe country at large. When he was\nnamed for Attorney General several\nleading democratic newspapers?one\nin particular?demanded the cancella-\ntion of the appointment, on the score\nthat Mr. Olney had all his life been i\nthe adviser of corporations, and on t\nthat account was unsuited for a place\nin a reform administration. I\nMr. Cleveland, however, was un- 5\nmoved. He knew his man, and held 1\non to him.\nMr. Olney made good in the Depart-\nment of Justice, and when Judge c\nGresham died he was transferred to\n3\nthe Department of State, where he j\nnot only made good, byt gained so\nmuch reputation that his name is ineluded\nin the list of great Secretaries I\nof State. It was his hand that traced 1\ne\nthe very stiff and pointed Venezuelan t\nmessage, which brought to a satisfae- 0\ntory settlement an old dispute which y\nhad threatened the friendly relations\nbetween Great Britain and America. J\nMr. Olney was the only member of\nthe second Cleveland cabinet to figure\nis a party influence after the admin- f\nistration ceased to exist. All the 1\ns\njthers, including Col. Lamont, a most 0\ntccomplished politician, passed from s\n;he scene forever. But Mr. Olney, to the\n-lose of his life, was one of his party's 1\neading advisers, and supported Mr.\nBryan in the latter's third campaign i:\nfor the presidency. A\n4\n1 1 q\nActivities in international finance j,\nire regarded by various statesmen as n\nlemanding for Uncle Sam the advisory\nassistance of a credit men's associa- l;\ntion.\nBernstorlf declares that Germany\n?me to grief through failure to take\n*is advice. Nearly every prominent\nwar German is assuming the same attitude\nwith reference to his own particular\ntheories of campaign. Nearly\nill will agree with Bernstorff's assertion\nthat the Berlin management of\nthe undertaking was stupid.\nThe fact that Liberia was not\ngreatly affected by war devastations\nloes not prevent that country from\nseing in financial circumstances that\nmake a loan most desirable to its interests.\nMuch of the distress in China is re.\nported to be in process of relief. Per- c\nhaps some of the political bosses of t\nthe celestial empire who have been 1;\nconcentrating all the wealth into their\nDwn fortunes have seen the economic 1\ndesirability of timely philanthropy. 6\nrhe hope is, however, not sufficiently\nreliable to obviate the need of every J\npossible effort the world over to meet r\nthe crisis.\n_____ f\nSHOOTING STARS.\ni\nBT PHILANDER JOHNSON.\nc\nScantiness. t\nro judge folks by the clothes they t\nwear\nIs very wrong, wise men have told, t\nBeneath the ragged jacket there 9\nA man may have a heart of gold. r\nt\nif clothes gave indication true, t\nTo a belief we'd be inclined\nrhat many a lady goes on view c\nWith very little on her mind. v\nResources of I.anenatrp.\n\"Don't you regard some of the lan- t\nguage in your speech as rather\nstrong?\"\n\"Yes,\" answered Senator Sorghum. c\n'I tried to make it so. My subject\nlad been so thoroughly discussed that t\na. little profanity seemed the only 1\nmeans of conveying a new impres- 0\nsion.\"\nA Farm Futurism.\n\"Hiram,\" said Mrs. Corntossel, \"do\nyou think the farmer has got all\nthat's coming to him?\"\n\"Not yet,\" replied her husband, as\ntie put on a fur overcoat and started\ntor his automobile. \"I'm waiting for\nthe predictions of some of these economists\nto come true. I'm in on the\nground floor in this agriculture business\nand what I'm lookin' forward to\nIs the development of a landed aristocracy.\"\nSimplified Ceremonies.\nWe view Inauguration day\nWith apprehension, though with\nI#> ?\"v b\nOh. Science! Pray devise a way\nTo havo the flareback simplified!\nt\nThe Grand Essential.\n\"What is the plot of your new\nplay?\"\n\"We haven't begun to think about\nthat,\" replied the producing manager.\n\"But you say you have a sure winner.\"\n\"We certainly have. We thought up\na. riskay title that'll bring the people\nin aa soon as they read the billboards.\"\nI\nv\nEditorial Digest\ni\nFrance Hopes for Naval Holiday.\nA writer in the French review Moni-\n:eur de la Flotte expresses the hope\nhat England and tlie United States\nan reach an agreement for a truce\n>f naval building. He analyses the I\nsituation as follows:\n\"The policy of intensive naval con-,\nstruction upon which America has\naunched would naturally lead to con-\n,'ersations with England, in these j\nimes of economic trouble it was j\nlifticult to understand that the chief I\nnaritime powers should start a new'\nace of armaments, madder still than j\nhat which was taking place in 1914,:\nmd it was especially astonishing to j\nlote that the signal for the struggle\nlad been given by just that nation i\nvhich had shown itself the most hos- j\nile to the principle of armaments.\n\"In spite of America's efforts.\" con-\ndudes the writer, \"she must realize j\nhat England will not easily allow the j\njcepter of the seas to be taken from j\nler. She is unquestionably superior in j\nvhat concerns personnel and techni- j\n\\nl experience. For this reason\nVmerica, knowing that continued na- j\n*al construction would increase Eng- j\nand's financial difficulties, would be\neady to accept the 'naval holiday,'\nvhich would mean not building any j\nnote ships for a certain period of j\nime. Probably America means that j\nhis should take place after her pro-\n;ram has been carried out,f which, as\nve have seen, would put^her in a su)erior\nposition to England as far as j\nnaterial is concerned. The alliance of J\nhe British and Japanese fleets, how- j\n?ver, would give the naval superiority\no these two. The British admiralty\n:an. therefore, start negotiations with j i\nhe United States without apprehen- j\nlion. We hope they will come to an I\nindorstanding and thus put an end j\no the uncertainty which hangs heavly\nover the naval destinies of the I\nvorld.\"\n)ur \"Secret Treaty\" as to Mexico.\nIt is not astonishing that the Spansh\npress, which is exceedingly jeaJous\n>f any move in the direction of inTeased\nNorth American influence in\n?atin America, should have become\noncerned over the reports of a secret\nreaty between the United States on\nhe one hand and England and France\n>n the other, under the terms of\nvhich Mexico is supposed to have be\nome an expioitaoie lerrilory.\nThe Madrid review Espana devotes\nlong article to the subject, in which\nt points out that, whether the treaty\nvas ever actually concluded or not, it\nan hardly be called a Vsecret.\" It is\n\"secret of Punchinello,\" declares the\nIspana, that these three powers do,\nn fact, regard Mexico as fit for forign\nexploitation and that they do\nacitly, at least, recognize certain pririties\nand a certain etiquette in the\nnatter, such, for example, as the\nlonroe doctrine.\nThe supposed treaty, declares the\nSspana, gives the United States a\n;ind of \"mandate\" over Mexico.\n\"An official of the Carranza governnent,\nJ-lilario Medina,\" says the Es>ana,\n\"undersecretary for foreign afairs,\npublicly declared in October,\n9ii0, that the said department posessed\nproofs In documentary form\nf an agreement between the United\nitates and the two great European\n'Ower9 for future partition of Mexlan\nterritory. An interpellation fol\nowed in the senate, demanding- tnat\nhese proofs be laid before that body.\nVirhaps the matter was dealt with\nn a secret session?at any rate, the\nlexican press has stopped discussng\nit.\n\"But in Europe and in the United\nItates the secret treaty against Metco\ncontinues to furnish a topic of\ntews and discussion 4s to its relaionship\nto the latent conflict between\nhe United States and Japan and Engand's\neventual attitude In that conlict.\"\nThe Espana goes on to say that\nvlien the subject was first broached\nnany considered it as a pure Gernan\ninvention, saying that Gen. Canlido\nAguilar. when in Europe, was\nihown forged papers by German\nigents. However, it adds, these pa>ers\nare in the Mexican archives,\nind. as Senor Medina speaks of them\nis authentic, it is possible that their\ngenuineness has been submitted to\nests. Nevertheless, no precise inbrmation\nhas been made public, and,\nvhile Mexican opinion has easily\n>een persuaded, \"foreign opinion is\nnore exacting, and insists on definite\niroofs.\"\n\"If Gen. Aguilar had been a hunorist,\"\nthe Espana goes on to say,\n'he would have said to the officious\nJerman agents who placed the myserious\ntext in his hand a brief word\nhat never fails to disconcert an inliscreet\ninformer?'old stuff.'\"\nA Good Sized Mandate.\nThe terms of the British mandate\n>ver Mesopotamia, concerning which\nnere nave oeen bo many questions\nitely, have just been published in IjOnlon.\nand, as the Paris Eclair (Briandst)\npoints out, they give wide pow:rs.\nThe Eclair says:\n\"The mandate proposed for Mesopoamla\ngives widespread power of occupation\nand government to the\nnandatory power. (Treat Britain has,\nor instance, the right of keeping\njarrisons throughout the country\nmtil public safety has been insured,\nihe has the control of foreign relaions\nof the country. She has the\nirotection of foreign subjects who\nire established there. But she must\nirganize a local government, work\n>ut a constitution, defend Mesopoamia\nagainst all aggression, watch\nhat no distinction is ma&e to the\niisadvantage of any foreign country,\no that commercial and petroleum enerprises\nof all countries are on the\nlame footing, and insure the free\niraotice of all religions, etc.\n\"The particular clause must be reained\nwhich obliges Great Britain\no present to the league of nations an\ninnual report on the way in which\nhe stipulations of the mandate are\n:acried out. The league of nations\nvould thus have a regular and effecive\ncontrol over the mandatory\nlower, which Is too often tempted to\nto beyond the power which is atributed\nto it.\nJ-The publication of the text of the\nnandate, which coincides with the delarture\no^ Mr. Churchill, the new\nolonial minister, for Egypt, where he I\nvill meet Mesopotamian delegates,\nooks as if it is going to be his duty\no get the terms accepted by the\nlopulations, and thus to make peace,\nvhieh would allow the costly British\nccupation to be given up.\"\nFrench Propaganda in America.\nLouis Thomas writes from America\n:o the weekly Opinion, Paris, that\nJen. Nivelle's visit is a good example\n>f the kind of propaganda France\n>ught to continue in the United\nstates. He says:\n\"Gen. Nivelle was invited by the\nJnited States to represent France at\nhe tercentenary celebration of the\nanding of the Puritans from the\nMayflower. As his mother was Eng.\nish, and he speaks English fluently,\nhis seems to have been a very happy\n:hoice, and he was enthusiastically\nvelcomed everywhere throughout the\n:ountry as the hero of Verdun. For\nhe people the war will be symbolized\n<y a few great names such as Joffre. the\nMarne, Dixmude,- Verdun, Petain,\ncoch, and the final victory of Maggin.\nrhis is really nisiory, me rest is tor\neholars and learned men.\"\nThis is what the Americans need,\n;ays the writer:\n\"Our great men must be sent to\n.hem, and especially those who apical\nto popular imagination. Gen.\nJlvelle's mission to the United States\nlas been a great success; we must\nlot forget that the Germans are very\n>usy trying to influence the United\nHates; but they cannot send conlueror\ngenerals. We can do it, and\nve must not hesitate to do so. We\nnust know how to consolidate the\nirestige of France. Whether dlplonatists\nor internationalists like it or\nlot. for many years only those\nfrenchmen should be exptfrted who\nvear a commanding officer's uniform.\"\ni Ribbed Vests\n1H\nWomen's White Ribbed Cotton\nVests, with taped necks?every\none perfect; a well- 4\nknown stand a. r d I\nmake\nI\nl:\n_\nend\n\n1\nFf F\n1 February\nThese sales arc getting to\nH and lowest prices are the ma\nP pers to Bargain Headquarters\nas good as the best but oh\nPRICE! SOME difference!\nI Spring Suits, '25&\nH Beautifully designed m trico\nand velours, in the new finger-tip\nsome beaded, others finished in e\nH Colors include reindeer, navy, brot\nSilk lined and all sizes.\n1\nSport Suits c\nWool Jersey\nEvery line in these suits is an\nC good quality and good workmanship,\nmatter the season?serviceable\nV and priced so that the most 1\neconomically inclined may pos- M\nsess one\n1,000 Waists-A Bi\\\nwith Important Sav\n1 Georgette Tub Silk White Pp\nm and Crepe de Chine Candy\nWaists Silk I\nI $2.98 $1.\nLovely new spring styles, New All-w\nI ^Hr0i\"ered and'-Ce K,im\" a'so natural ti\nmed, in porcelain blue,\nhoney d